data: The site of this family vacation home is a clearing with a spectacular slope of nearly 20m plunging into the jungle. perched on top of the hill, a canopy roof opens to the north and west on the vast landscape and tree tops as far as the eye can see. It houses a base divided into three platforms following the natural terrain topography and is designed in continuity with the outdoor decks and the infinity pool. The only tree on the site is maintained and fully integrated into the heart of the living space. The leveling work of the base was carried out to optimize the roof: the three suites are stacked to enjoy the same spectacular view sheltered by retractable shutters and a double-oriented cathedral volume is released to accommodate a living space with vertical circulations that can be seen while an office space is installed on a mezzanine in the background. Upon arriving from the access easement, a large hermetic screen facade ensures the privacy of the occupants and participates in the mystery: nothing reveals such an opening and spaces deliberately erasing the boundaries of inside and outside.
Restructuring and renovation of an apartment

Aging and outdated, the heavy renovation of this apartment, which had undergone a large number of transformations that altered its spatial qualities, was an opportunity for the MOA and the MOA to carry out a complete recomposition with a limited budget. Consisting of a large, open living space and a separate kitchen as well as two suites (bedrooms, dressing rooms, bathrooms) at the top of a 1950s building located on the Seine quays in the 16th arrondissement of Paris, a clear distinction has been made between the two suites and the living space. The latter consists of a square of nearly 7m x 7m where the original parquet has been preserved, restored and opened on its entire width on a balcony running, welcoming a living room, a dining room and a bar-library.

This "jenga" bar leans on a decimated post, a relic of the removal of all superfluous circulations. Composed of a series of boxes in folding of raw steel patinated, it structures the space by allowing to circulate all around in order to access the different adjoining spaces. In direct connection with the kitchen, its 2m long counter allows to enjoy from the back of the room an unobstructed view of the city and the Eiffel Tower, multiplied by a continuous and full-height mirrored wall that a round and colorful niche interrupts and animates. Through the reflection, this mirrored wall allows to establish on the same plane, a dialogue between the geometry and the contrasted colors of the niche-display case and that delimiting the TV corner. Both freely revisit in three dimensions chromatic compositions of the Bauhaus painter Josef Albers. The kitchen, which can be opened to the living room by means of a sliding door, is designed with great sobriety. It is characterized by a contrast between the bright white of its massive lacquered facades and a matte anthracite on the floor and on the worktops, as well as on the blown glass of the hand-made suspensions.

The separation between the living room and the suites is realized through a thick partition of 70 cm allowing to create an additional threshold for each suite but this thickness also allows to integrate all the storage, technical ducts, heating system, a water closet, a laundry room and niches. If the large living room is designed as a reception and meeting place, colorful and open to the city, the suites on the other hand are treated as retreat spaces and of great chromatic neutrality consisting of a soft contrast of white and light gray that is systematically applied to walls, floors and ceilings. The work of indirect lighting allows to create a cottony atmosphere on unified surfaces that animate the oxidized and patinated steel sconces designed in collaboration with the artisan Rosalie Pericaud. In the bathrooms, round mosaic planes bring touches of texture to the white sides of the worktops and Italian showers.

Vieillissant et aux quipements vtustes, La rnovation lourde de cet appartement, qui a subi un grand nombre de transformations ayant altr ses qualits spatiales, fut l'opportunit pour la MOA et la MOA de procder  un recomposition totale avec un budget limit. Compos dun grand espace de vie dcloisonn et dune cuisine spare ainsi que de deux suites (chambres, dressing, salle de bain)- au sommet dun immeuble des annes 1950 situ sur les quai de Seine du 16e arrondissement de Paris, une distinction claire a t faite entre les deux suites et lespace de vie. Ce dernier consiste en un carr de prs de 7mx7m o le parquet dorigine a t conserv, restaur et ouvert sur toute sa largeur sur une balcon filant, accueillant un coin sjour, une salle  manger et un bar-bibliothque.

Ce bar  jenga  vient sappuyer sur un poteau dcentr, reliquat de la suppression de toutes les circulations superflues. compos dune srie de boites en pliage dacier brut patin, il structure lespace en permettant de circuler tout autour afin daccder aux diffrentes espaces attenants. En connexion directe avec la cuisine, son comptoir long de 2m permet de profiter depuis le fond de la pice dune vue imprenable sur la ville et la Tour eiffel, dmultiplie par une paroi miroir continue et toute hauteur quune niche ronde et colore vient interrompre et animer. A travers le reflet, cette paroi miroir permet dinstaurer sur un mme plan, un dialogue entre la gomtrie et les couleurs contrastes de la niche-prsentoir et celle dlimitant le coin tl. Toutes deux revisitent librement en trois dimensions des compositions chromatiques du peintre Bauhaus Josef Albers. La cuisine pouvant souvrir sur le salon au moyen dun galandage est pense dans une grande sobrit. Elle se caractrise par un contraste entre le blanc brillant de ses facades en laque massive et un anthracite mat au sol et sur les plans de travail, ainsi que sur le verre soufl des suspensions faites mains.

La sparation entre salon et les suites est ralise  travers une cloison paisse de 70cm permettant de crer un seuil supplmentaire pour chaque suite mais cette paisseur permet aussi dintgrer lensemble des rangements, des gaines techniques, du systme de chauffage, un watercloset, une buanderie ainsi que des niches. Si le grand salon est pens comme un lieu de rception, et de rencontre, color et ouvert sur la ville, les suites quant  elles sont traits comme des espaces de retraite et de grande neutralit chromatique consistant en un doux contraste de blanc et de gris clair qui sapplique de faon systmatique aux murs, sols et plafonds. Le travail de lclairage indirecte permet de crer une atmosphre cotonneuse sur des surfaces unifies quaniment les appliques en acier oxyd et patin conues en collaboration avec lartisane Mtallire Rosalie Pericaud. Dans les salles de bain, des aplats de mosaques rondes viennent apporter des touches de textures aux pans blancs des plans de travails et des douches  litaliennes.

For a long time a vacant lot, the site of the villa, located south of Rabat, faces a significant vis--vis to the west, consisting of a row of houses. Strict urban rules of development apply there. Designed for a couple in their forties with a busy lifestyle and their three children, the villa tries to reconcile their desire for openness and intimacy, combining convivial spaces for entertaining friends and family and others offering the possibility of peace and quiet. In alignment with the street, the villa has two monolithic and mute volumes. Once past the fence and the altimetric games of the garden, this silent architecture reveals open and sheltered spaces.

Compact, the house is organized on three levels. On the garden level, an atrium serves the vertical circulation, a kitchen, a living room and a generous living space. Open 180 to the garden, it extends through large sliding windows to two terraces to the east and west. Like courtyards, these terraces are real additional spaces sheltered from the summer heat and the Atlantic trade winds and animated by glimpses of the sky through large oculi. The first floor is divided into two wings on either side of the atrium. On the one hand, the master suite installed within the levitating monolith and opening onto a vegetated terrace to the south and an east-facing patio dedicated to the bathroom space. On the other hand, three bedrooms each with a private bathroom and a planted balcony. 

Finally, thanks to the raising of the garden level, a third level discreetly opens onto an English courtyard planted in a semi-basement. The atrium plays a key role in the spatial organization of the villa. It articulates and connects all levels. Its spectacular volume, magnified by natural zenithal lighting, offers many visual porosities and remains unsuspected from the outside. Contrasting with the horizontality of the living room, the verticality of the atrium allows, in the event of a heat wave, to play a role as a "wind tower" and to naturally ventilate and cool the heart of the house. The bold articulation of sculptural volumes is counterbalanced by simple and raw materials: matte white wash on plastered concrete, veined walnut wood, bouchard Taza stone and patinated raw steel. This deliberately restricted palette is complemented by touches of sky and vegetation typical of the Moroccan Atlantic coast that can be found at all levels inside and outside.
